Basic Descriptive Charts

Bar Plot Number of Executives by Race and Gender

ggplot(execs, aes(ethnicity, fill=gender)) +
  geom_bar() +
  xlab("Race/Ethnicity") + 
  ylab("Number of Executives") +
  ggtitle("Number of Executives's by Race/Ethnicity and Gender") +
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Gender")) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Boxplot Salary by Gender

ggplot(execs, mapping = aes(gender, salary)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  ylab("Salary in $1000's") + 
  ggtitle("Executive Salary by Gender") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Boxplot Salary by Race and Gender

ggplot(execs, mapping = aes(ethnicity, salary, color=gender)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("Race/Ethnicity") + 
  ylab("Salary in $1,000's") + 
  ggtitle("Gender Gap in Executive Salary by Race/Ethnicity") +
  guides(fill=guide_legend(title="Gender")) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Scatter Plot Salary with Trend Line, Age and Gender

ggplot(execs) +
  geom_point(aes(age, salary, color=gender), alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(age, salary)) +
  xlab("Age") + 
  ylab("Salary in $1,000's") +
  ggtitle("Executive Salary by Age and Gender") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Scatter Plot Salary with Trend Line, Age and CEO

ggplot(execs) +
  geom_point(aes(age, salary, color=ceo), alpha = 0.25) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(age, salary)) +
  xlab("Age") + 
  ylab("Salary in $1,000's") +
  ggtitle("Executive Salary by Age and CEO Status") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Basic Linear Models

Salary versus Gender (T-test, Part I)

pander(t.test(salary ~ gender, data = execs))
Welch Two Sample t-test: salary by gender
Test statistic df P value Alternative hypothesis
-3.379 78.22 0.001138 * * two.sided

Salary versus Gender (T-test, Part I)

t.test(salary ~ gender, data = execs)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  salary by gender
## t = -3, df = 80, p-value = 0.001
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -215  -56
## sample estimates:
## mean in group FEMALE   mean in group MALE 
##                  621                  757

Simple Linear Model

#Salary by Gender
lm_1 <- lm(salary ~ gender, data=execs)

# Make Model Table
# To Knit PDF's Change This to type="latex"
stargazer(lm_1, header=FALSE, type='html',
          font.size = "footnotesize", 
          title = "Linear Model of Executive Compensation by Gender" )
Linear Model of Executive Compensation by Gender
Dependent variable:
salary
genderMALE 135.000**
(58.000)
Constant 621.000***
(57.000)
Observations 1,000
R2 0.005
Adjusted R2 0.004
Residual Std. Error 439.000 (df = 998)
F Statistic 5.400** (df = 1; 998)
Note: p<0.1; p<0.05; p<0.01

Note That the Ttest and Linear Model Have the Same Estimate:

\[ \text{Ttest Mean} = \beta_{Males} + \alpha \]

\[756.97 = 135.493 + 621.475 \]

Some Basic Linear Models

#FORMAT:
#model_name <- lm(DV ~ IV, data=YOUR_DATA)

#Salary by Gender
lm_1 <- lm(salary ~ gender, data=execs)

#Salary by Age
lm_2 <- lm(salary ~ age, data=execs)

#Salary by Race/Ethnicity
lm_3 <- lm(salary ~ ethnicity, data=execs)


# Make Model Table
